,Recommended,224940,21227923,"Posted: 15 February, 2016",all,saltmummy626,"Exposition simulator! I had this game on the playstation 2, I remember a lot about it. More than anything though, I remember the cutscenes. Interaction between characters who would jawjack each other for so long, you could make a grilled cheese and a pot of chicken noodle from scratch (start it boiling anyway) and still get to see the end of the cutscene. Seriously. The shortest cutscene I can remember is near the end of the game and involves a short interaction with a large demon. It's about the length of a standard cutscene in a regular game. The long as hell cutscenes serve to explain a bit of the worlds backstory a bit and can give you the general idea of what the world is about. Sort of. You still need to play the older legacy of kain games to really understand, but they aren't required to understand this particular games story or enjoy the gameplay.A word of warning when it comes to the combat btw, you can lock onto an enemy while fighting, it's a bit janky but without it you're basically relegated to swinging wildly and hoping to hit enemies, even if you use a controller. In the late game with those demons I mentioned, that wild swinging crap does not work out. You must lock onto them or you are going to have a hard time. I beat this game several times, and most of the combat I did in ALL my playthroughs consisted of running in circles, ""jousting"" with enemies using the light attack and then running away only to come back and land another, single, hit and run away again."
,Not Recommended,224940,20514126,"Posted: 13 January, 2016",all,Zeke,"Another trip down Nostalgia lane, but unlike the first Soul Reaver, this one hasn't aged as well.PROS:+This is the best version of Soul Reaver 2. Besides widescreen problems, the game runs fine at 60 frames a second.+The story continues and, like the first game in the series, it is masterfully written.+The puzzles are pretty good.+You can use the wraith blade whenever you please, which is very, very good--see below.CONS:+/- The game repeats itself a little too much. You run through the same areas at least three times. It reminds me of the hub-style gameplay of the first game, but it's done much worse. But it pales in comparison to the other issues.CONS:-This is the worse game in the series when it comes to the combat. It a phrase: It's broken. You have a heavy attack and can block now, nice; but the heavy attack is too slow to hit and the enemies' block does not reduce their health, nor does it ever break. You almost HAVE to use the reaver to kill enemies. The AI is horrible, too, since it will keep striking you without pause, not even letting a single hit in. It gets annoying when the enemies can both block everything you have and instantly 7hit combo you to death.-There are too many enemies. This game obviously has enemy placement that feels copy-paste, almost to the point that I wanted to stop playing.All in all, this is the worst game of the series, lagging behind Soul Reaver one, and bounds worse than much better Blood Omen 2. I'd only recommend this game if you want to see how the story plays out, but even then, you can easily read a synpopsis on this one (or just the script) and be fine."
